<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: A parade featuring kimono-clad girls, samurai and floats will be
the highlight next Sunday of the San Francisco Cherry Blossom Festival, which
is in progress today at the Japan Center.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CHILDREN; RECREATION; ENTERTAINMENT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  CHILDREN'S Day Around the Bay is being held today with activities and
entertainment at five Bay Area locations: Lucile Salter Packard Children's
Hospital at Stanford, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.; Ghirardelli Square, San Francisco, 1
to 6 p.m.; Oakland Coliseum, tailgate 3 to 5 p.m., games at 5 p.m.; Great
America Theme Park, Santa Clara, 10 a.m. to 9 p.m.; and the PruneYard,
Campbell, 1 to 3:30 p.m.;    The event is a benefit for Ronald McDonald House
and the new children's hospital at Stanford. Today is the dedication and
opening of the hospital, a non-profit, regional referral center bringing
together the pediatric programs previously offered by Children's Hospital at
Stanford and Stanford University Hospital.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ALL-DAY, ALL-BAY CELEBRATION FOR KIDS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Family Clipboard  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Cherry blossom season;  San Francisco's Cherry Blossom Festival, scheduled
in a two-weekend format, is in progress today at the Japan Center, Post and
Buchanan streets, San Francisco. Taiko drum groups from Tokyo will perform
along with Japanese classical and folk dancers and musicians. Japanese
culinary arts demonstrations, arts and crafts and martial arts, costumes and a
food bazaar will be featured at the Japan Center site, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. today
and during the same hours Friday through next Sunday. A 2 1/2-hour Cherry
Blossom Festival parade at 1 p.m. next Sunday will highlight the event.;   
The parade will begin at City Hall and travel 15 blocks to Japantown. Featured
will be costumed Japanese dancers and musicians, armor-clad samurai, floats,
Akita dogs, taiko drummers and more.;    San Jose's cherry blossom festival,
"Nikkei Matsuri," will be held 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. April 28 at Fifth and
Jackson streets, San Jose. (408) 298-4303.;    (box) Cats galore are
congregating in the South Bay with two cat shows, both opening Saturday. The
Aristicats Cat Club is holding "A Feline Coronation." The 12-ring, all-breed
championship and household pet show will be held 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. Saturday
and next Sunday at the Santa Clara County Fairgrounds, 344 Tully Road, San
Jose. $4 single adult, $10 family (two adults and two children), $2 children
ages 12 to 15, and $1 seniors.;    The Santa Clara Valley Cat Fanciers show
will be held 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Saturday and next Sunday at the San Jose Civic
Auditorium Exhibit Hall, 291 S. Market St., San Jose. More than 300 cats will
compete. $4 adults, $2 children and seniors.;    (box) Earth Day Every Day,
part of San Jose Beautiful Month, will be held 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Saturday at
City Plaza Park, San Carlos and Market streets, San Jose. Food and
entertainment, an all-electric sports car that can travel 70 mph and a
carnival. Free.;    (box) Other family activities this week include:;   
Events; Israel's 43rd Anniversary  will be celebrated 12:30 to 5 p.m. next
Sunday with Joel Nelson's orchestra, folk songs, a petting zoo, food and
carnival rides. Jewish Community Center, 14855 Oka Road, Los Gatos. Free.;   
Senior Expo  takes place 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Saturday and next Sunday at the
Santa Clara County Fairgrounds, 344 Tully Road, San Jose. Families are invited
to attend with their senior members. Entertainment, how-to demonstrations,
arts and crafts, medical screening tests and food. Free. (408) 295-3050.;    A
Spring Kids' Dance  will be held 5 to 8 p.m. today in Ben Lomond. Bring a dish
to share at the family potluck. Sponsored by the Peace on This Planet for
Children, the event will be held at Park Hall on Mill Street, Ben Lomond. $2
adults, free for kids. (408) 336-5607.;    Model Railroad Open House  will be
at the South Bay Historical Railroad Society, featuring N, HO, On3 and G scale
operating trains. 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Saturday and next Sunday at the CalTrain
depot, 1005 Railroad Ave., Santa Clara. $1.50 adults, 50 cents children, $4
family maximum.;    Upcoming; Downtown Mountain View Parade,  to an "Animal
Crackers" theme, will be at noon April 27. More than 1,500 participants will
dance, march, juggle and sing their way from Evelyn and Castro streets to
Pioneer Park, Church and Castro streets, where there will be a post-parade
celebration, including a contemporary big band jazz by Tuesday Night Live.
Free.;    Milpitas Young Artists' Fair  will be held April 27, 9 a.m. to 4
p.m., with live entertainment, workshops in visual and performing arts,
exhibits and food. Community Center, 457 E. Calaveras Blvd., Milpitas. (408)
942-2470.;    Lorrie Morgan,  a rising country-western singing star, performs
at 4 p.m. at an all-day spring outing April 28 at the Santa Clara County
Fairgrounds, 344 Tully Road, San Jose. From noon to 7 p.m. there will be pony
rides, a magic puppet show and refreshments. The outing is a fund-raiser for
the Community Coordinated Child Development Council of Santa Clara County. $8
adults, $2 children 12 and under, and $20 family ticket (two adults and
unlimited children).  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  DOROTHY PRIES, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE>
